At scale, in country viral sequencing has worked in many places, and grown over time (eg in US, UK, Netherland, Denmark and Germany). Data sharing has been good, but we have a cross-current between rapid public health needs and fast and open research needs/opportunities to solve

Modelling with open data has been surprising success across the world (excellent models from French, Swiss, German, UK, US scientists) but the integration of scenario planning models with healthcare and societal behavioural models has been ad-hoc at best.

Much of the understanding of the infection, immune evasion and hospitalisation of different variants and vaccines was driven from analysis in 4 countries - Denmark, Israel, UK and South Africa - why not more places?

It has been surprising too that in this emergency there was only one setting (UK) that ran at-scale clinical trials allowing many potential treatments to be tested and accepted (dexamethasome) or rejected (many feasible cases).

We've also learnt alot about the practical end of large scale public health. Japan, South Korea and Germany all had excellent to good public health interventions from the start - what in detail worked, and how do we get that detail to map across into other settings?
Even partial understanding of these aspects (and we already have some) will allow some guesses about interventions from drugs to other therapies ready to test.

We've learnt a huge amount about this specific virus, and we're still at the foothills of some big questions - why is COVID the disease triggered in some individuals and not others? what are the long term auto-immune like consequences described as LongCOVID?

I know both scientists and public health professionals will not get a rest; monitoring new variants, working out how to have effective and affordable surveillance, working out how to improve response and having tested plans for another possible immune escape variant.

This will not be the last of SARS-CoV-2 though - it will circulate worldwide, and the lack of vaccine accessibility globally is a stark indication of how a global problem (a virus which infects humans) requires a global response. We must do better now and in the future.
Looking up, society in the developed world will largely have to rebuild and readjust post Omicron wave; plenty of things here outside of my expertise directly.

In countries with more entrenched skepticism of vaccines, for a whole host of reasons, such as Greece or Romanian  + (I think) Poland, I think the Omicron wave will still be complex to navigate. The US, where Omicron is raging+vaccine coverage far from ideal in places shows this.

That said, this is just one part of Germany which has a high provision of hospital beds including ICU beds with established ways to share capacity across Lander. As such this is probably feasible to navigate.

It has been impressive in fact how consistent Germany's response has been given this federal structure (contrast perhaps to the US) but the stronger-than-France vaccine in elderly population in Saxony and Thuringia must cause the Chancellory planners concerns.

If such fatal flaws are discovered in papers, we need a better system than anonymous Twitter accounts tweeting about it, and hoping that some bigger accounts notice.And @planetmoney and @paulmromer needs somewhere to read about this, before they promote the flawed study further

I think it's worth thinking about the broader implications for science.This paper is an obvious pollution of our knowledge pool. How could this be avoided? Peer-review clearly isn't enough. I posit that we need a system of *post-publication peer review*.
(You can now also read more about the study here: https://t.co/YtW1rgMxwV, and here: https://t.co/k4t1df2eJi )

But that's not what happened. Instead the paper was published, passed peer review, and has been accepted as a solid part of the scientific body.In fact, no one seemed to have noticed this disqualifying flaw until @AnechoicMedia_ tweeted about it:https://t.co/L8TkhYVqXF
In fact you shouldn't draw any conclusions from it. At most it could be published as a partial data set, with a note about it's limitations.

It is worth dwelling on how exceedingly obvious this problem is. Of course, if you get most of your data points from a source that ends in 1900, you will have fewer data points after that. You should not start making grand conclusions about society and innovation from this.
Another study gathered the data in a less biased way, and found that there was essentially no fall in patenting rates after 1900https://t.co/EL52Zwk96v https://t.co/9ZS2T8rjed

All we know is there was a source up to 1900 that provided more Black patents data to her data set up to 1900 but not after. We have no reason to think that the large fall in her data set after 1900 is not solely caused by this.

Now in her study, the main claim she is making is that the fall in Black patents has a real world cause (violent acts).The problem is that we have no reason to think there actually was a fall in Black patents in 1900.

If you get data from one bountiful source, and that source only lasts until a certain date, it is obvious that you will have fewer data points in the time period after this date.And indeed this is what we see in the figure. After 1900, there are fewer Black patent data points.

The data about Black patents she collected herself, and 65% of the Black patents in her data were from a data set curated in 1900.For Black patents after 1900, she got the patent data from different sources.

Once I do prepare seeds from the fruit I have stored, I'll have some fruit leftover to see if they too will last for so very long.
I don't have a hash tag associated with this project yet, but anything I've posted about tomatillos in the last few years is likely related content.

However, since they're all storing well, I can be pretty confident all the seeds this year carry the storage trait.This coming spring, I'm hoping to plant quite a few plants in the tomatillo project so I can start selection for fruit size/color/etc.

All the fruit from the current generation is also storing well. I was worried some plants wouldn't have the trait and so any seeds from this year could have included genetics from a pollen donor that didn't.

A couple coworkers were chatting about food insecurity and how often more healthy food is also more perishable, so costs more.This reminded of my ongoing storage tomatillo project. The last generation of plants produced fruit which stored at room temperature for a year.

Fascinating to watch; clearly the role of consumers (and consumer regulation) is to shift primarily using electricity based power for everything. Love to have pointers to any more in depth analysis on these topics.

It is interesting how well Contract for Difference has worked for wind power (and critically how fast the CfD price has dropped for offshore wind - far faster than expected is my understanding), but how do you get the right market in storage?

The complex thing is also how to  design market(s) to achieve the societal goal (low carbon on demand electricity) as cheaply as possible given responsible safety and closing out technology options is bonkers.
With this big mix of renewables, interconnectors, storage, fission and fusion it seems a very solveable problem to have plenty of low carbon electricity on demand at the right time.

In one meta-level above, there is both exisitng big nuclear fission, small nuclear fission and it seems like it is possible (nowhere guarenteed though!) fusion power on the horizon, with regulation (fission) and plenty of technology pushing (fusion) barriers.

I am also fascinated to see how things like liquid air energy storage (eg https://t.co/3jGYAyAzu7) plays out - if this is liked pumped hydro but can be built in many locations, then not only can one provide storage but also place that storage more strategically.

Even then I could imagine things like dedicated batteries to effectively increase the absorbative capacity of a facility for energy which then can run a more continuous addition energy storage (say, for example, H2 production) to make the capital investment work.
Eg, a 10% round trip efficiency system which is low capital and can absorb plenty of energy fast may well be far more useful than a 20% round trip efficiency system with higher capital costs.

I am very much an amateur here, but in the situation of ultimately plenty of energy - just at variable times (eg, wind) - one needs critically low(er) capital and high(er) capacity absorbation energy storage schemes - efficiency is less important (or rather goes to capacity)

A new paper by Marie Schoelmerich, a postdoc in my lab, https://t.co/HniPTRna5B, reports discovery of Methanoperedens plasmids. They are very different from Borgs. The plasmids may open the way for genome editing of these uncultivated methane oxidizing archaea within communities

Our next frontier is to deploy CRISPR to change the genomes of microbes that we cannot cultivate. A central challenge is how to get the editing tools into the cell. Uncultivated organisms themselves may hold the key. Plasmids may be the Trojan horses...
Later, this approach was relabeled metagenomics. Metagenomics led us to viruses and CRISPR systems. Such systems are the source of technologies upon which Metagenomi is built

In 2002, most microbes that we were interested in could not be grown in the laboratory, so essentially nothing was known about them. My lab studied acid mine drainage biofilms and in 2004 showed that you can learn about uncultivated organisms via reconstructing their genomes

Metagenomi is founded on metagenomics, a method that enables the discovery of genes in DNA sequences from natural microbial communities. The development of metagenomics has been a large part of my life’s work

In summary, most avian introgression patterns are in line with Haldane's Rule, but have to be validated with estimates of hybrid fitness and other field observations. And genomic data provide exciting opportunities to gain more insights into the basis of Haldane's Rule.(14/14) https://t.co/BSnFRpQO6f

Moreover, not a single study included W-linked loci. This is understandable because this sex-chromosome is extremely difficult to sequence. With new genomic tools it will be possible to explore this chromosome and study its connection with Haldane's Rule.(13/14) https://t.co/tyQC3JIfWn

Most genomic studies provide a genome-wide average of introgression (including in my own work) instead of estimating local introgression rates. Relating introgression of particular genomic loci to hybrid fitness is an exciting avenue for further research.(12/14) https://t.co/UMYM4xpu0D

During my literature search, I found only a few genomic studies. This caveat is partly due to my strict search criteria (see paper for details), but also reflects the recent focus on finding barrier loci instead of quantifying introgression across the genome.(11/14) https://t.co/GSXfGbqwon
my bf presented an R report of my cat to his work 😻💕in love💕😻 https://t.co/DIcMcPDR2X

I also uncovered two exceptions to Haldane's Rule. The deviating pattern in mallard and spot-billed duck hybridization was due to sex-biased dispersal. And the exception in black-browed and sooty tit can be explained by ancient introgression.(10/14) https://t.co/RBdGNtfigr

To confidently invoke Haldane’s Rule, one has to provide convincing evidence for reduced fitness of female hybrids. And only two studies did this... One on nightingales and one of saltmarsh sparrows. Here, field observations were crucial in complementing genetic studies.(9/14) https://t.co/f5like4gJX

However, just because an introgression pattern follows Haldane's Rule does not mean that this is due to reduced fitness of female hybrids. Other mechanisms, such as mate choice, local selection pressures or sex-biased dispersal, might explain the patterns.(8/14) https://t.co/5RhW0QGaxI
And indeed, using a variety of methods, the majority of studies reported introgression patterns in line with Haldane's Rule.(7/14) https://t.co/3CLPKrpo9w

I tested these expectations by conducting a literature review which focused on studies that directly quantified introgression rates for autosomal, sex-linked and mitochondrial loci.(6/14) https://t.co/Buf946S39v

Second, the faster evolution of Z-linked loci and the hemizygosity of the Z-chromosome in females might speed up the accumulation of incompatible alleles on this sex-chromosome, resulting in lower introgression rates for Z-linked loci than for autosomal loci.(5/14) https://t.co/EgXBO1uIM4
First, maternally inherited loci (i.e. mitochondrial and W-linked loci) might show lower introgression rates than biparentally inherited loci (i.e. autosomal loci).(4/14) https://t.co/EgNphOK1kX

This pattern has been confirmed for numerous taxa, but I wondered whether it also extends to the molecular level. 🤔If female bird hybrids are less fit compared to male hybrids, you can expect certain patterns in the introgression of particular genetic loci.(3/14) https://t.co/eFu7wn3AGg

In this study, I took a closer look at one of my favorite rules in biology: Haldane's Rule, which states that the sex with different sex-chromosomes will show the greatest fitness reduction in a hybrid cross. In mammals, this is males (XY) and in birds females (ZW).(2/14) https://t.co/xOnTOsnTHy

Hats off to Adam and … read the book :)

@AdamRutherford’s book takes you through this - in the US, in U.K. and in Germany in particular (where eugenics had its horrible  consequence of supporting the Holocaust). He writes with honesty and a lightness of prose given the bleak and horrible topic.

Science is fascinating and the thrill of understanding the world a bit better and being able to know how some things work (if I do this … then this…) can be seductive and compelling, and then harnessed for good or evil in society

Going back to eugenics, it is not just the ugly writings of Karl Pearson that we need to look at but also Marie Stopes (women’s rights, abortion) and Kellogg’s (breakfast cereals to this day) commitment to eugenics.
Scientists can tend to examine the details of these cases (models, off targets etc) of without framing this in societal terms - society must agree to these uses of science.

And in the US the self regulation around IVF and fertility clinics allow selection of embryos for implantation via polygenic risk scores, something I strongly believe has very little benefit and much real hazard.

And future abuse of genetics / genomics technology is not some piece of abstract science. A couple of years ago a Chinese scientist (illegally it turns out) performed genome editing on two human embryos, later born.
This history doesn’t make modern genetics or frequentist statistics wrong and the best way for the science to flourish is to be cognisant of the past

It is … pretty bleak …. But I am sure we have to know and understand that history to untangle both genetics and statistics from it. Simply eliding over it both allows the echos of that wrong science to persist and we don’t guard against future abuse of science
Genetics as a science has it roots entangled completely with eugenics, and these roots also give rise to much of frequentist statistics in particular from the work of Pearson and Fisher.
The history of eugenics and now the potential modern rebirth as embryo editing / PGS selection on embryos is I think a must read for *every* geneticist.

(I’m a friend of Adams and we’ve each sharpened our arguments and communication around genetics, race and other topics in discussions along with @JenniferRaff @aylwyn_scally @minouye271 and @StuartJRitchie amongst others)

I can completely recommend this book - Adam is thoughtful scientist / science communicator combined excellent, easy to read writing on a dark and horrible part of science history - and science present https://t.co/NZuOBft5PU

Overall one might have to anticipate another bump in the road. While cases appear to have peaked in the UK they are still very high and BA.2 has the potential to delay the decline or even cause a rise. In Germany the height and duration of the wave is likely to be longer.

The relatively slower spread of BA.1/1.1 over the Christmas break coincides with reduced contact patterns in the UK.This *might* suggests that Omicron has a particular growth advantage in settings with larger numbers of contacts.https://t.co/V4SNLxLO9f

What's also interesting is that in all three countries BA.1*s advantage over Delta dipped somewhat over Christmas and picked up again in January.No such drop was seen for BA.2 in the UK or DE. As BA.2 was very rare at the time, possibly an influx of cases masked the effect. https://t.co/gXZcaoHPId

In Germany all lineages are rising (r > 0). BA.1.1 has overtaken BA.1.Even though the absolute growth advantages are a bit lower - potentially due to ongoing restrictions - the relative order BA.2 > BA.1.1 > BA.1 > Delta/Otheris the same. https://t.co/4sbTZgvw0G

In Denmark, BA.2 was introduced earlier and has outcompeted BA.1.As in the UK, BA.2 has the greatest growth advantage, followed by BA.1.1.BA.1 and BA.1.1 cases have been falling (r < 0) in recent weeks.BA.2 has been growing throughout, but appears to be peak now. https://t.co/8Z3cStbpq8

In the UK, BA.1 and BA.1.1 grew rapidly (r > 0) in late November and early December. BA.1 cases have been shrinking since Christmas.Yet BA.1.1 and BA.2 cases are both increasing, the latter at ~15% per day.

In our agent-based model (HoPE) pigeon-agents ignore the position of the predator and just turn away from its heading while coordinating with each other through alignment, attraction and avoidance. Their escape rule is thus independent of their distance to the predator https://t.co/16VbGkeirn

A recent study showed that pigeon flocks when attacked by a robotic falcon increase their escape frequency and decrease their alignment as the predator gets closer. We studied how this pattern arises in a new model adjusted to empirical data (top: real, bottom: model data) https://t.co/51XfR3DLYZ

We contend that semiconductor and nanopore-based #sequencing systems provide the best path to fully analyzing this complex biology. Moreover, we think these technologies have matured enough, gained enough commercial traction, and are sufficiently funded to go the distance.

A second takeaway is that detecting the presence of a molecule is NOT the same thing as fully characterizing it. The lightish-purple slope illustrates (to scale) how processes like alternative splicing, mutations, and PTMs can turn 20,000 genes into >1M proteoforms.

Let's revisit the central dogma, zooming back out to focus on multi-omics -- not just proteins. If there's one thing to take away from this chart, it's that each successive layer of biomolecule (DNA, RNA, etc.) is substantially more complex than the last. https://t.co/rJxGCfOsAE

Using these tools, scientists should get unprecedented access to the proteome, from <10% as recently as 2000, to about 50% today, to potentially >95% in a few years. Sometimes, innovation appears invisible until it happens all at once.https://t.co/DFHbR4YUjG https://t.co/FdPpY85a6b

You can read more about these here:https://t.co/LweCji3FWjhttps://t.co/BSspYlNSd1The point is that new detectors aren't guaranteed to work or diffuse quickly. Until then, easy-to-adopt sample prep and AI tools can continue improving MS today.

I've written about @seer_bio's nanoparticle technology already, which lives at the front "bookend" of mass-spec. https://t.co/SXKP2bw2H0Meanwhile, tools like @InterVennBioSci's OpenPip and Scanning SWATH leverage deep-leaning to debottleneck error-prone and tedious analysis.

Let's not forget about mass-spectrometry (MS), a ubiquitous #proteomics method. We argue that you can teach an old dog new tricks. That is, MS is undergoing a sample-prep + AI facelift that should continue maximizing the value of the technology, as shown below. https://t.co/ChUs6rtxB9

You can read more about these methods here. https://t.co/QI9Nn1JZ56https://t.co/SFtdaMelMxhttps://t.co/Kmqkxfc5ddWhile there are still technical risks, we think several of these approaches will gain traction throughout the next five years - greatly decreasing $/protein.

Some of the truly new protein detection methods enable the same 'massively-parallel' analysis that allowed #NGS to deflate quickly in price while causing demand to surge. These approaches are based on things like proximity extension, aptamers, and iterative epitope binding.

While we don't share the perspective that proteomics is more 'valuable' than other 'omics, we agree that scalable, cost-effective (clinical) proteomics technologies are immensely powerful. https://t.co/sA07vqqlZZ
